[2] Michigan
Date: Mon 17 Sep 2012
Source: Fox17 [edited]
http://www.fox17online.com/news/ionia/fox17-ehd-deer-deaths-more-than-double-in-kent-county-20120917,0,1265571.story


There are hundreds of new reports of deer deaths throughout West Michigan coming in to the Department of Natural Resources (DNR) as epizootic hemorrhagic disease, or EHD, spreads to new deer populations. The massive die-offs are caused by a virus associated with the disease that's spread by flies.

The hardest hit county is still Ionia, with 50 new cases reported, bringing the total number of reported cases to 1660. In Kent County, there were 85 new cases according to the DNR, more than double the number bringing the total to 126.

Updated numbers from other counties haven't been released, but there have been already more than 3100 cases statewide as of Monday [17 Sep 2012] evening, according to DNR Wildlife Biologist John Niewoonder. He says more new numbers for other counties could be ready for release Tuesday [18 Sep 2012].

FOX 17 spoke with a hunter [from] Oakfield Township in Kent County Monday [17 Sep 2012]. [He said] he's found as many as 40 dead deer on the 3-acre property he typically hunts on each fall. He says the deer are coming to the marsh area sick and dying on the spot. "I walked a perimeter pond right there and [saw] a total of 39 deer."

There are so many deer bodies in such a small space, the area smells like decomposing deer. "This particular piece I found 7 bucks dead yesterday [12 Sep 2012], the rest were all does and fawns," [said the hunter].

[The hunter] and his dad, have been trekking through the woods and fields in the rural area, trying to count the animals.

The DNR says the deer are being found near or in water because they are trying to cool off due to high fevers associated with the virus.

"It`s absolutely devastating, a lot of us try to manage the deer herd, shoot older deer if we can. When you put all this effort into a piece of property and then you go for a walk in early fall and you find all your deer dead, it's hard to express in words. It`s terrible," [he said].

The deer may only get some relief when the region experiences a hard frost which will kill the biting midge fly that carries the virus. The fly breeds in mud and the dry summer has created a bumper crop.

If you find dead deer, the DNR will not come out and pick them up. Biologists say you will have to bury them or let nature takes its course.

They are asking that you call your local DNR field office when you spot deer that are dead and have no other injuries, such as those caused by a car. Biologists believe there are hundreds if not thousands of deer deaths that will go unreported because people will not find the deer. They hope folks call in so they can get an accurate count of how many deer will die off this season.

Niewoonder says Michigan has never experienced an outbreak of EHD like this before. Although there have been some mild outbreaks in the past, he says it's been nothing like this year's outbreak. He says typically this is a disease that is associated with the warmer, southern states of the US.

[Byline: Jennifer Dowling]

